  "prompt": "What is the IUPAC name of CCl3?",
  "response": "The molecular formula CCl\u2083 represents a trichloromethyl group, which is a functional group consisting of a carbon atom bonded to three chlorine atoms and one additional atom or group. However, CCl\u2083 by itself is not a complete molecule; it is a radical (a species with an unpaired electron) and is called the **trichloromethyl radical**.\n\nIf CCl\u2083 is part of a larger molecule, the name would depend on the context. For example:\n- If it is attached to a hydrogen (CCl\u2083H), the molecule is **chloroform**, with the systematic IUPAC name **trichloromethane**.\n- If it is attached to another atom or group (e.g., CCl\u2083Br), the name would incorporate \"trichloromethyl\" as a substituent.\n\nThus, the standalone IUPAC name for CCl\u2083 as a radical is **trichloromethyl radical**.",
